For recovering the possession itself he had a iudicium secu- torium or Cascellianum, which was an actio arbitraria, enabling the judge to condemn the party in possession to pay the value of the property ln dispute in desault of restitution, Gaius iv. 165, 166.

None of these proceedings, however, provided for the trial of the real question at issue: they presupposed its decision in favour of the lower bidder at the fructus licitatio, and were designed to enable him in that event to recover the possession and damages for having been awhile deprived of it. The real question—which of the parties was, at the issue of the interdict‚ entitled in law to the possession (Gaius iv. 166), was brought to trial in the form of a wager, or rather of two wagers, as each party played a double rble. Now in Roman law a wager or a bet could be made only by two stipulations, each of which was ground sor an independent action: the first party promised the second so much, if he turned out to be in the wrong3 and then the second promised the first the same sum in the contrary event.
